elements.title: Wilhelmine Holmboe
elements.contents: ... that the mezzo-soprano Wilhelmine Holmboe (pictured), who studied in Paris with Pauline Viardot and moved to Italy to perform, was one of the first Norwegian women to be acclaimed internationally for her singing?

elements.title: Faith Cabin Library at Seneca Junior College
elements.contents: ... that Faith Cabin Library at Seneca Junior College in South Carolina is also called the "Oberlin Unit" because of the donations of books by the students of Oberlin College in Ohio?

elements.title: Martha Yujra
elements.contents: ... that as a member of the El Alto Workers' Center, Martha Yujra participated in mass mobilizations that led to the resignations of two Bolivian presidents?

elements.title: Central City College
elements.contents: ... that Central City College was established as an African American-led alternative to the historically black Atlanta Baptist College?

elements.title: Arlene Kelly
elements.contents: ... that Arlene Kelly made her international debut for the Ireland women's cricket team after nine of their regular players were unavailable for selection?

elements.title: One Griswold Street
elements.contents: ... that One Griswold Street in Detroit, now owned by the Church of Scientology, was built on the location of the first church building in the city, Ste. Anne de Détroit?

elements.title: Lady Eva Julius
elements.contents: ... that Lady Eva Julius once called Girl Guiding "the most important youth movement in the world"?

elements.title: Gould Memorial Library
elements.contents: ... that the Gould Memorial Library once hosted pie-throwing contests to raise money?
